english:
  title: Preface to the Miscellaneous Poems of Master Duncun
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: 'I first beheld Master Duncun at the small study of Master Goeuun, newly escaped from the calamity wrought by the traitor Shin Don. He had journeyed from the south, his bearing dignified and resolute, his spirit full and luminous, his words ringing clear and precise in their eloquence. My heart marveled at him. I saw him again at the thatched cottage of Master Mogeun, who received me with such respect that day seemed to slip away unnoticed. I listened to his discourse, and later, when Master Toyeun invited both Master Mogeun and Master Goeuun, along with Master Duncun, to a modest gathering where we placed a potted plum blossom before us and composed linked verses on the plum flower, I too attended and heard his brilliant lines. After this, when I moved my household to Seonjjeong Valley, I found myself but a few leagues from his grass pavilion beneath Yongsu Mountain. He sent me a poem on chrysanthemums, which I reverently answered, and through this began to realize my cherished wish to follow in his company. Not long after, Master Duncun fell ill and passed away. In the years that followed—more than ten—Masters Goeuun and Toyeun successively departed, and Master Mogeun too ascended to heaven. I alone remain, and now when I recall those days of fellowship, they seem as dreams half-remembered. Alas, what sorrow surpasses this? The poems and writings of the Three Masters have all been transmitted to the world, yet Master Duncun alone had nothing. This troubled me greatly. Now his son, the Court Assessor Jik, came bearing his father''s manuscripts and showed them to me, saying: "My late father wished to realize all he had learned, yet office denied him such fortune. He wished to fulfill his purpose, yet his span of years was not long enough. Your unworthy son carries a grief that shall not end with life itself. I have heard it said that to illuminate and honor one''s parents is the ultimate filial duty, yet how dare I presume to such? My only wish is to carve these several hundred poems into print and transmit them to posterity, so that scholars of later ages who study the ancients may know my father''s name. I humbly ask that you grace these pages with a preface." Hearing this, my sorrow deepened. Reading through his poems all day, I found that which he called his spirit full and luminous, his words ringing clear and eloquent—all of it lies woven within the very rhythm and resonance of the verse. The ancients said that poetry cannot be feigned—was this not truly spoken? Master Duncun had three sons, all of whom passed the examinations and became renowned for their learning and virtue. The Court Assessor is his eldest, and with unwavering dedication seeks to illuminate his father''s excellence and transmit his father''s name to all. Surely such filial devotion deserves our admiration.'
  footnotes:
    - Shin Don (신돈) was a powerful Buddhist monk and official during the Goryeo dynasty who wielded considerable influence before his fall from power, which occurred around 1371.
    - The 'Three Masters' (三隱) refers to Masters Goeuun (고은), Toyeun (도은), and Mogeun (목은)—renowned scholars and poets of the Goryeo-Joseon transition period whose works were preserved and published.
    - The composition of linked verse (連句) on plum blossoms was a refined literary practice among educated circles, where multiple poets would contribute alternating stanzas on a given theme.
    - The 'Yongsu Mountain' (龍首山) was a location in the Seoul area associated with scholarly retreat and study during this period.
